    <h2>Containers and Columns</h2>
    <p>The content area is managed with a container/column approach similar to material design and tailwind.css</p>
    <h3>The default container</h3>
    <p>Most of the pages and content should use the default container classes: </p>
    <ol>
      <li><cyan-code>{'<div class="container">'}</cyan-code> as a row for each "line" of columns</li>
      <li><cyan-code>{'<article class="column">'}</cyan-code> as a column element</li>
      <li><cyan-code>{'<article class="column large">'}</cyan-code> as a main column element</li>
      <li><cyan-code>{'<article class="column small">'}</cyan-code> as a small column element</li>
      <li><cyan-code>{'<article class="column auto">'}</cyan-code> as a column that fills the container depending
        on content size.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>The container auto-sizes to fit 2 columns, a large column wiht a small column, or a column with 2 small columns. Other
      combinations are discouraged, and will need to be managed with custom styles.</p>
    </p>
    <p>The column sizes also support /md/wd prefixes to enable different layouts for different screen sizes.
      For example, <cyan-code>{'<div class="column md-auto wd-large">'}</cyan-code> will make a column be 
      maximum available size on tablets and large on desktop.</p>
  </article>

